Title: Comprehensive C++ Guide: Understanding and Applying Basic Objects, Classes, Linked Lists, and File I/O

Unit 3a: Basic Objects, Assignment, and Strings

3.1 Basic Objects (Structs)
A struct in C++ is similar to a class, but it is a default public, and all members are visible outside the struct, unlike classes where members are private by default. Define a struct as follows:

```cpp
struct Name {
  string firstName;
  string lastName;
};
```

3.2 Assignment of Objects
To assign one object to another, use the '=' operator:

```cpp
Name a;
Name b;
a = b; // copies members from b to a
```

3.3 . (Dot) Operator
To access members of a struct, use the '.' operator:

```cpp
a.firstName = "John";
a.lastName = "Doe";
```

3.4 -> (Arrow) Operator
Use the '->' operator to access members when the struct's name is stored in a pointer:

```cpp
Name *p = &a;
p->firstName = "Jane";
p->lastName = "Smith";
```

3.5 Use of getline()
getline() function is used to read a whole line from an input stream. It reads a line until it encounters a newline character '\n' or reaches the end of the input stream.

```cpp
#include <iostream>
#include <string>

int main() {
  std::string line;
  std::getline(std::cin, line);
  std::cout << "You entered: " << line << std::endl;
  return 0;
}
```

3.6 Checking an Input Stream for Failure
Use the 'failbit' flag to check for input stream failure:

```cpp
std::ifstream inputFile("input.txt");
if (inputFile.fail()) {
  std::cout << "Error opening file!" << std::endl;
  return 1;
}
```

3.7 Using C++ string class
Strings in C++ are handled using the std::string class. Here's an example of using string concatenation and comparison.

```cpp
#include <iostream>
#include <string>

int main() {
  std::string str1 = "Hello";
  std::string str2 = "World";
  std::string str3 = str1 + " " + str2;
  if (str1 == "Hello") {
    std::cout << "str1 equals 'Hello'" << std::endl;
  }
  std::cout << str3 << std::endl; // prints "Hello World"
  return 0;
}
```

Unit 3b: Defining Your Own Classes

3.8 public vs. private
public members can be accessed from outside the class, whereas private members can only be accessed from within the class:

```cpp
class MyClass {
 private:
  int _privateMember;
 public:
  int publicMember;
};
```

3.9 Constructors and Destructors
A constructor is a special function that initializes an object when it is created. A destructor is a special function that cleans up an object before it is destroyed.

```cpp
class MyClass {
 public:
  MyClass(int initValue) : _privateMember(initValue) {}
  ~MyClass() { /* cleanup */ }
 private:
  int _privateMember;
};
```

3.10 Defining Member Functions
Define a function inside a class with the 'void' keyword if it doesn't return anything and with the return type if it does:

```cpp
class MyClass {
 public:
  void myFunction() { std::cout << "Hello!" << std::endl; }
  int myFunctionReturningInt() { return 42; }
 private:
  int _privateMember;
};
```

3.11 Splitting Your Class into Files
It's a good practice to split the implementation and declaration of a class into different files:

```cpp
// Class declaration in MyClass.h
class MyClass {
 public:
  void myFunction();
 private:
  int _privateMember;
};

// Class implementation in MyClass.cpp
#include "MyClass.h"
void MyClass::myFunction() { std::cout << "Hello!" << std::endl; }
```

Unit 4a-d: Linked Lists, vectors, deques, and doubly linked lists

These concepts involve creating and manipulating different data structures using C++. For a comprehensive understanding, it's recommended to refer to the "C++ Primer" or "Effective C++" books or other reputable resources for a deep dive into these topics. Here's a brief overview:

4.1 Linked Lists: A data structure where each element (node) contains data and a pointer to the next element.

4.2 Vectors (vector<T>): A dynamic array that can resize itself.

4.3 Deque (deque<T>): A double-ended queue that supports adding and removing elements from both ends efficiently.

4.4 Doubly Linked Lists: A data structure where each node contains data and pointers to both the next and previous nodes.

Unit 4e-f: Syntax and use, advantages of passing by reference, const references, checking for file failure, and File I/O

4.5 Syntax and use: These concepts cover the syntax and usage of C++ features like passing arguments by reference and const references.

4.6 Advantages of Passing by Reference: Passing by reference allows updating the original variable instead of passing a copy. Improves performance when working with large objects and allows functions to modify the data in the calling function.

4.7 Const References: In C++, a const reference is a reference that cannot be reassigned. Use the 'const' keyword before the '&' symbol to declare a const reference.

4.8 Checking for Failure When Opening a File: Use the 'is_open()' member function to check if the file stream is open.

4.9 Using C++ ifstream and ofstream classes for File I/O: These classes are used to read from and write to files using C++.

Aim to learn one concept at a time and practice writing the code and understanding its working in depth before moving on to the next topic. Happy coding!
